<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    Factory LAN SKU/sync backend uses HTTP on the local 192.168.1.10 network;
    cleartext is explicitly permitted for that specific factory IP host.

    The Jetson Xavier NX inference unit (WS4) is different: its LAN IP is not
    known at build time; it's whatever address the factory network assigns
    the specific device an operator pairs with on the floor, entered by the
    operator in the pairing screen, not compiled in. Android's Network
    Security Config has no wildcard/CIDR domain matching, only exact
    domain/IP entries, so a per-Jetson domain entry is not workable here.

    Given every network call this app makes stays on the factory LAN by
    design (auditNoCloudInference in build.gradle.kts greps src/main for
    cloud-provider hostnames and fails the build if any appear; see that
    task before assuming this is looser than it looks), the base-config
    fallback below permits cleartext broadly rather than to a fixed Jetson
    IP. This is a real, deliberate broadening of the cleartext policy versus
    the single-IP-pinned approach used for the Server, flagged here and in
    the WS4 PR description, not silently done. A tighter alternative (e.g. a
    custom TrustManager/NetworkSecurityPolicy keyed to the paired IP at
    runtime) is a legitimate follow-up if this is judged too broad.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <domain-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true">
        <domain includeSubdomains="false">192.168.1.10</domain>
    </domain-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true" />
</network-security-config>
